ding.   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   mentions a witness to a set of deeds who is variously named as John  <i>ad portam</i>, John  <i>le Porter</i>, and John  <i>atteyate</i>, 1322–6 in   Yorks Deeds   (Wadworth, WR Yorks).  Compare  Yeatman  ,   Gate   locative name for someone who lived at or came from Yate (Gloucs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Yorks Deeds","meanings":["English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Duket</i>. This may sometimes have been an early Middle English pet form of an Old English * <i>Ducc(a)</i> but was more often a pet form of  <i>Marmaduke</i>, especially in Yorks (  See  Duke  ). Willelmus filius Duket of Hackness (NR Yorks) may have been related to Marmaduke de Sneaton, who lived in the neighbouring village of Sneaton (1301 in   Subsidy Rolls  ). Dukett de Thweng, 1416 in   Yorks Deeds   (Snaith, WR Yorks), was probably identical with or a relative of Marmaduke de Thweng, 1404 in   Inquisitiones post Mortem   (York)."]},{"name":"Yeatman","meanings":["English (southern): occupational name for a gate-keeper, from Middle English <i>yate</i> + <i>man</i>. Compare   Yates  ."]},{"name":"Gate","meanings":["Anglo-Saxon: Geat, a gate"]},{"name":"Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames","meanings":["English: variant of   Bulcock  .   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   notes that in the parish registers of Bolton by Bowland (WR Yorks) the same family name is spelled  <i>Bulcock</i>,  <i>Bowcocke</i>, and  <i>Boocock</i> (1608–30), and that Edward Bowcock of Howgill (WR Yorks) is also called Bulcock in a will dated 1677. Compare also Alice Bowcock, 1641, Chr. Bulcock, 1646 in   IGI   (Barnoldswick, WR Yorks)."]},{"name":"Yates","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>yates</i> ‘gates’, plural of <i>yate</i>, Old English <i>geat</i> ‘gate’, hence a topographic or occupational name for someone who lived by the gates of a town or castle and who probably acted as the gatekeeper or porter. Compare   Gates  . Alternatively, a variant of the singular form <b>Yate</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Atwater","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone whose dwelling was by a river or lake, Middle English <i>atte water</i> ‘at the water’.","History: This surname was established from an early date in New England. David Atwater was one of the group of settlers who founded the New Haven colony in 1638."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":49,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"G. Yate Atwater was born from 1210 to 1235, in England as the son of Atwater. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"from 1210 to 1235–":"1210 kuni 1235–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1238–1318":"1238–1318","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","1238":"1